Alternative forms[edit]

  • duābus sedeō sellīs

Etymology[edit]

Literally meaning "I sit on two saddles". Compare the Icelandic bera kápuna á báðum öxlum (“to carry the coat on both shoulders”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /duˈaː.bus ˈsel.liːs ˈse.de.oː/, [d̪ʊˈaː.bʊs̠ ˈs̠ɛl̠.l̠iːs̠ ˈs̠ɛ.d̪e.oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /duˈa.bus ˈsel.lis ˈse.de.o/, [d̪uˈaː.bus ˈsɛl.lis ˈsɛː.d̪ɛ.ɔ]

Verb[edit]

duābus sellīs sedeō (present infinitive duābus sellīs sedēre, perfect active duābus sellīs sēdī, supine duābus sellīs sessum); second conjugation

  1. to fall between two stools, keep in with both parties, to sit on two stools, to wear two hats
